We can keep going to merge the “ME” proteins. The ME1,ME2,ME3 are different be their topological structure on the cell membrane. So it will be possible and reasonable to merge them into one single category that will be called “ME”.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
yeast_merge <- yeast %>%
  mutate(localization = case_when(
    localization %in% c("ME1", "ME2","ME3") ~ "ME",
    TRUE ~ localization
  ))

table(yeast_merge$localization)
## 
## CYT EXC  ME MIT NUC POX VAC 
## 463  35 258 244 429  20  30

As such, there will be 7 categories for the final data analysis step. They are: CYT – Cytoplasm EXC – Excretion (outside the cell) ME – Cell Membrane MIT – Mitochondria NUC – Nucleus POX – Peroxisome VAC – Vascular

Calculate th pearson residuals:

obslabel = cbind(yeast_merge$localization=="MIT",yeast_merge$localization=="CYT", yeast_merge$localization=="EXC", yeast_merge$localization=="ME",yeast_merge$localization=="NUC",yeast_merge$localization=="POX",yeast_merge$localization=="VAC") * 1
prd_prob_bo2 = fitted(model_bo)

fitted_m = sapply(2:(ncol(obslabel)), function(m){
  fit_m <- prd_prob_bo2[rowSums(obslabel[,c(1,m)]) > 0,c(1,m)]
  fit_m <- fit_m[,2] / rowSums(fit_m)
})

resP.bo <- sapply(2:ncol(obslabel), function(m) {
  # baseline is column 1 here 
  # otherwise you should replace "1" with the corresponding index and adjust the range of "m" accordingly
  obs_m <- obslabel[rowSums(obslabel[,c(1,m)]) > 0, m]
  fit_m <- prd_prob_bo2[rowSums(obslabel[,c(1,m)]) > 0,c(1,m)]
  fit_m <- fit_m[,2] / rowSums(fit_m)
  (obs_m - fit_m) / sqrt(fit_m * (1 - fit_m))
})


# plot
par(mfrow=c(2,2))

plot(fitted_m[[1]], resP.bo[[1]], xlab="Fitted probability for class CYT vs MIT", ylab="Pearson residual",
     sub = "spar = 0.9")
lines(smooth.spline(x = fitted_m[[1]], y = resP.bo[[1]], spar=0.9), col=2); abline(h=0,lty=2)

From the GAM model, we can see the non-linearity between variables and response is not that significant. The majority source of the non-linearity would come from the boundaries in which the samples are not clustered. The wide gap among the samples in the peripheral region can lead to the sudden change in the fitting function, which causes the non-linearity. However, we do observe some hidden non-linearity that was not revealed from bo model. Some example would be:
